<tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="1"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Administrative Law</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:  
              </b>Slamming; Standing to file a complaint for violation of § 505 
              of the Michigan Telecommunications Act (MTA); Protection under § 
              506(3) for an unintentional and <i>bona fide</i> error; Award of 
              costs and attorney fees as sanctions under § 506(4); Finding of 
              responsibility for two violations of § 502(a); Adjudication of a 
              violation of § 502(b) not alleged in the complaint; Lack of material 
              prejudice<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:  
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Published)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:  </b>LCI Int’l Telecom Corp. v. Michigan Pub. Serv. Comm’n<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:  </b>12374<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Per Curiam – Kelly, White, and Talbot</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The defendant-Commission’s 
              determination that the wife of the customer of record for the telephone 
              service had standing to file a complaint for violation of § 505 
              of the MTA was neither unlawful nor unreasonable. Section 506(1) 
              of the MTA does not restrict the term “person” to end users, providers, 
              or the Public Service Commission, and the statutory language was 
              reasonably read to permit “any person alleging a violation of section 
              505” to file a complaint. The court also concluded that plaintiff-long 
              distance provider was not entitled to protection under § 506(3) 
              on the basis its reliance on a forged letter of authorization to 
              change service was an inadvertent and <i>bona fide</i> error. The 
              statutory language specified an unintentional error, not a deliberately 
              fraudulent act such as forging a signature. However, the Commission 
              erred in awarding costs and attorney fees based on a finding that 
              plaintiff’s defenses were frivolous. Although plaintiff failed to 
              prevail, its positions were not devoid of arguable legal merit. 
              The violations, fines, and reimbursements ordered were affirmed, 
              but the imposition of sanctions was reversed.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12374.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
<tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="2"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Bankruptcy</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Whether a hearing should be held when motion to convert is filed 
              prior to debtor's motion to dismiss; §§ 1307(b) and (c)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. Bankruptcy Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>In re Cowper<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12356<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Stevenson</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The court concluded 
              that when a motion is filed to convert a bankruptcy from chapter 
              13 to chapter 7 prior to a debtor's motion to dismiss, a hearing 
              should be held to consider the merits of the conversion motion before 
              ruling on the debtor's motion to dismiss. A creditor filed a motion 
              to convert citing several transgressions on the part of the debtors. 
              The issue before the court concerned the tension between a debtor's 
              right to dismiss a chapter 13 case under § 1307(b) and a creditor's 
              right to seek a conversion of a case under § 1307(c). The court 
              opined that it did not believe Congress did not contemplate that 
              a debtor could prevent conversion under § 1307(c) by simply filing 
              a motion to dismiss whenever and for whatever reason. The court 
              ordered that a hearing be held on the &quot;cause&quot; element 
              prescribed by § 1307(c). </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/090601/12356.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
<hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Trustee fees in a chapter 11 case; Statutory construction related 
              to § 1930(a)(6) quarterly fees to trustee <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. Court of Appeals Sixth Circuit<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>In re Danny's Markets, Inc.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12368<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Martin, Nelson, and Rice</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The trustee 
              fees in a chapter 11 case must be based on the amount of all payments 
              until the case is converted, dismissed, or closed. The court considered 
              the effect of the 1996 amendment to the bankruptcy code on the scope 
              of &quot;disbursements&quot;, a critical term in these cases, after 
              a chapter 11 reorganization plan has been confirmed. The trustee 
              claimed that the debtor had not paid any fees between the date of 
              confirmation and the date the case was closed. The debtor acknowledged 
              that it owed some fees, but contested the trustee's insistence that 
              the statutory basis for the fees included all of its expenditures 
              during that time. The court concluded that Congress contemplated 
              that disbursements will encompass all payments to third parties 
              directly attributable to the existence of the bankruptcy proceeding, 
              and that throughout the proceeding, these payments' essential character 
              will not change. Accordingly, all of these payments, including the 
              debtor's day-to-day, post-confirmation operating expenses, must 
              be accounted for in the calculation of the trustee's quarterly fee. 
              Affirmed.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/us_appeals/2001/092101/12368.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>        
<tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="3"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Civil 
            Rights</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Constitutional Law</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Alleged § 1983 violation arising out of altercation at police 
              station; Alleged violation of Fourth Amendment right against unreasonable 
              seizures; Qualified immunity; Vicarious liability<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Jones v. Robinson<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12359<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Bell</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Since plaintiff 
              suffered no injuries as a result of an incident where the defendant-animal 
              control officer touched her arm while attempting to prevent plaintiff 
              from entering a room where an allegedly stolen cat was being kept, 
              defendant was entitled to a judgment as a matter of law because 
              any temporary seizure of plaintiff's person was not unreasonable. 
              The cat was considered stolen property by the police and it appeared 
              to defendant that plaintiff was determined to enter the room, grab 
              the cat, and leave with it. Defendant used minimal force to prevent 
              plaintiff from entering the room. Plaintiff did not allege that 
              defendant prevented her from leaving the police station. In fact, 
              the police encouraged her to leave. Police had a duty to the cat's 
              owner not to let plaintiff take the cat. Under these circumstances, 
              plaintiff was never the subject of a &quot;seizure&quot; of her 
              person within the meaning of the Fourth Amendment. Even assuming 
              that defendant's touching of plaintiff could have been considered 
              a seizure, his actions did not rise to the level of an &quot;unreasonable&quot; 
              seizure.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/090501/12359.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Corrections</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Failure to exhaust administrative remedies<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. Court of Appeals Sixth Circuit<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Jones v. Smith<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12370<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam – Daughtrey, Gilman, and Cohn </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The district 
              court order properly dismissed without prejudice plaintiff’s complaint 
              filed under the Americans With Disabilities Act against a prison 
              counselor and physician for failure to exhaust administrative remedies. 
              Plaintiff argued that he had not exhausted his administrative remedies 
              because, when he asked one of the defendants, his counselor, for 
              a grievance form, the counselor told him to get out of his office, 
              and that it was futile to require exhaustion in his case. Plaintiff 
              did not allege that there was no other source for obtaining a grievance 
              form, or that he made any other attempt to obtain a form or to file 
              a grievance without a form.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/us_appeals/2001/092101/12370.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
<hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Corrections</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b>  
              Whether plaintiff-prisoner could bring suit against defendants-prison 
              officials in their individual capacities for violation of the anti-retaliation 
              provision of the American with Disabilities Act (ADA); Recovery 
              for emotional and mental injuries in light of § 1997(e) of the Prison 
              Litigation Reform Act (PLRA); Michigan Persons with Disabilities 
              Civil Rights Act (MPDCRA); Injunctive relief under the ADA and the 
              Rehabilitation Act; Monetary damages under the Rehabilitation Act<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:</b>  
              U.S. District Court Eastern District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b>  Key v. Grayson<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:</b>  12364<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):</b>  
              Gadola</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The court held 
              that the ADA’s anti-retaliation provision, § 12203(a), created no 
              individual liability for defendants, current or former prison officials, 
              for allegedly retaliating in relation to the provision of public 
              services. Plaintiff-prisoner claimed that defendants violated the 
              ADA, the Rehabilitation Act, and the MPDCRA by denying him services 
              because of his hearing disability, and retaliating against him for 
              filing suit. The court also held that § 1997(e) of the PLRA was 
              no obstacle to plaintiff’s recovery for mental or emotional damages 
              because that section’s effective date was after plaintiff filed 
              suit and the provision was not retroactive. The court dismissed 
              plaintiff’s MPDCRA claim without prejudice because it would best 
              be adjudicated in state court. In all other respects, the court 
              adopted the magistrate judge’s report and recommendation, which 
              was included with the court’s opinion.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/090501/12364.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="4"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Constitutional 
