            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Civil Rights</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Alleged § 1983 violation arising out of altercation at police 
              station; Alleged violation of Fourth Amendment right against unreasonable 
              seizures; Qualified immunity; Vicarious liability<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Jones v. Robinson<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12359<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Bell</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Since plaintiff 
              suffered no injuries as a result of an incident where the defendant-animal 
              control officer touched her arm while attempting to prevent plaintiff 
              from entering a room where an allegedly stolen cat was being kept, 
              defendant was entitled to a judgment as a matter of law because 
              any temporary seizure of plaintiff's person was not unreasonable. 
              The cat was considered stolen property by the police and it appeared 
              to defendant that plaintiff was determined to enter the room, grab 
              the cat, and leave with it. Defendant used minimal force to prevent 
