        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="5"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Corrections</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Civil Rights</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Failure to exhaust administrative remedies<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. Court of Appeals Sixth Circuit<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Jones v. Smith<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12370<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Per Curiam – Daughtrey, Gilman, and Cohn </font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The district 
              court order properly dismissed without prejudice plaintiff’s complaint 
              filed under the Americans With Disabilities Act against a prison 
              counselor and physician for failure to exhaust administrative remedies. 
              Plaintiff argued that he had not exhausted his administrative remedies 
              because, when he asked one of the defendants, his counselor, for 
              a grievance form, the counselor told him to get out of his office, 
              and that it was futile to require exhaustion in his case. Plaintiff 
              did not allege that there was no other source for obtaining a grievance 
              form, or that he made any other attempt to obtain a form or to file 
              a grievance without a form.</font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/us_appeals/2001/092101/12370.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Civil Rights</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b>  
              Whether plaintiff-prisoner could bring suit against defendants-prison 
              officials in their individual capacities for violation of the anti-retaliation 
              provision of the American with Disabilities Act (ADA); Recovery 
              for emotional and mental injuries in light of § 1997(e) of the Prison 
              Litigation Reform Act (PLRA); Michigan Persons with Disabilities 
              Civil Rights Act (MPDCRA); Injunctive relief under the ADA and the 
              Rehabilitation Act; Monetary damages under the Rehabilitation Act<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:</b>  
              U.S. District Court Eastern District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b>  Key v. Grayson<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:</b>  12364<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):</b>  
              Gadola</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The court held 
              that the ADA’s anti-retaliation provision, § 12203(a), created no 
              individual liability for defendants, current or former prison officials, 
              for allegedly retaliating in relation to the provision of public 
              services. Plaintiff-prisoner claimed that defendants violated the 
              ADA, the Rehabilitation Act, and the MPDCRA by denying him services 
              because of his hearing disability, and retaliating against him for 
              filing suit. The court also held that § 1997(e) of the PLRA was 
              no obstacle to plaintiff’s recovery for mental or emotional damages 
              because that section’s effective date was after plaintiff filed 
              suit and the provision was not retroactive. The court dismissed 
              plaintiff’s MPDCRA claim without prejudice because it would best 
              be adjudicated in state court. In all other respects, the court 
              adopted the magistrate judge’s report and recommendation, which 
              was included with the court’s opinion.</font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/090501/12364.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="6"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Criminal 
            Law </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3" valign="top"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Environmental Law</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b>  
              Violation of 36 C.F.R. § 1.5(a)(1) (operating a permanently installed 
              on-board vessel generator in a prohibited area); Isle Royale National 
              Park regulations; Whether the quarter of a mile prohibition was 
              invalid, or arbitrary and capricious; Public notice; Whether regulation 
              was overbroad; Whether defendant was engaged in a First Amendment 
              protest action<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:</b>  
              U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b>  United States v. Bieti<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:</b>  12358<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):</b>  
              McKeague</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Defendant’s 
              misdemeanor conviction for violating 36 C.F.R. § 1.5(a)(1) by operating 
              a permanently installed on-board vessel generator in an area prohibited 
              by Isle Royale National Park regulations was affirmed because the 
              regulatory scheme did not authorize his conduct and the quarter-mile 
              prohibition was not arbitrary and capricious. Defendant admitted 
              at trial that on the date in question his boat was anchored in Duncan 
              Bay, the on-board vessel generator was running, and he was within 
              a quarter-mile of the Duncan Bay campground. Defendant was incorrect 
              that 36 C.F.R. § 2.12(a)(3) allowed him to operate his on-board 
              vessel generator within a quarter-mile of the campground. Defendant’s 
              argument that the quarter-mile setback was arbitrary and capricious 
              was also without merit, and since he admitted he knew about the 
              prohibition, he was not prejudiced by any alleged failure to provide 
              public notice. </font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/091301/12358.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:  
              </b>Sentencing; <i>Apprendi v. New Jersey</i>; Viability of <i>United 
              States v. Pruitt</i> after <i>Apprendi</i>; <i>United States v. 
              Stafford</i>; Effect of defendant’s stipulation to amount of drugs 
              for which he was held responsible; <i>United States v. Harper</i>; 
              Federal witness anti-gratuity statute; <i>United States v. Ware<br>
              </i></font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:  
              </b>U.S. Court of Appeals Sixth Circuit<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:  </b>United States v. Roper<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:  </b>12371<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):  
              </b>Gilman, Clay, and Wallace</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Defendant waived 
              his <i>Apprendi </i>argument regarding the amount of drugs for which 
              he was responsible when he expressly agreed to the drug quantity 
              provided in the PSR in exchange for the government’s agreement not 
              to seek a sentence enhancement for possession of a firearm. This 
              holding was consistent with the decision in <i>Pruitt</i>. A question 
              was raised at oral argument whether <i>Pruitt</i> survived <i>Apprendi</i>, 
              and the court concluded that issue was resolved in<i> Stafford</i>, 
              where the court reasoned that defendant’s factual admissions obviated 
              any possible concerns about the proper standard of proof. The court 
              concluded that <i>Stafford </i>applied here since defendant, although 
              he initially objected to the drug quantities found in the PSR, withdrew 
              his objection at his sentencing hearing and expressly acknowledged 
              that he was accountable for that amount, which provided the required 
              factual basis to sustain his sentence. The judgment of the district 
              court was affirmed. </font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/us_appeals/2001/092101/12371.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="7"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Employment 
            &amp; Labor Law </font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="top"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Tax</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>The State Employees Retirement Act (SERA); Whether the trial 
              court properly determined that monthly payments for accumulated 
              sick leave under a state employee early retirement program were 
              exempt from state, county, city, and other local taxes; Rights and 
              accruals; <i>Ejusdem generis</i>; Absurd result; Necessary joinder; 
              Local taxing authorities; Injunction<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Published)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Stone v. Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12373<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Whitbeck and Kelly; Dissent - Collins</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The Court of 
              Claims properly determined that monthly payments to state employees 
              (hired before October 1, 1980 and retired under the SERA) for accumulated 
              sick leave under a special statutory provision for an early retirement 
              program, are exempt from state, county, city, and other local taxes. 
              Ordinarily, payment for accumulated sick leave to state employees 
              hired before 1980 occurred in a single lump sum, which the state 
              taxed as income the year it was received. The SERA provides that 
              any amount that a member retiring under § 19(f)(3) would otherwise 
              be entitled to receive as a lump sum at retirement on account of 
              accumulated sick leave shall be paid in 60 consecutive equal installments. 
              When the state began making monthly accumulated sick leave payments 
              to plaintiffs under the 1996-97 early retirement program, the state 
              taxed these payments as if they were the traditional lump sum payments, 
              apparently withholding both state and local taxes from the payments. 
              Plaintiffs claimed that defendants could not tax these monthly payments. 
              The court concluded that the Legislature intended to make the tax-exempt 
              provisions of § 40(1) apply to the accumulated sick leave payments 
              under § 19(f)(3). Affirmed</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12373.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Litigation</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b> 
              ERISA; Disability benefits; Motion for judgment on the administrative 
              record<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Lamoreaux v. Medtronic, Inc. <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12354<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Bell</font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The 
              decision of the defendant’s ERISA board terminating plaintiff's 
              long-term disability benefits was reversed and plaintiff’s benefits 
              were reinstated retroactively. The court found that the great weight 
              of the evidence indicated that plaintiff was disabled under the 
              provisions of the ERISA plan and that the plan administrator was 
              in error. The objective evidence in the record supported the conclusions 
              of plaintiff’s doctor and an independent doctor selected by defendant 
              that plaintiff was disabled. Defendant also asserted that there 
              were at least six jobs in the area that plaintiff was capable of 
              performing, but the weight of the evidence indicated that plaintiff 
              simply could not perform these jobs. The court granted plaintiff's 
              motion for judgment on the administrative record.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/082801/12354.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
<tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="8"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Environmental Law</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Criminal Law</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b>  
              Violation of 36 C.F.R. § 1.5(a)(1) (operating a permanently installed 
              on-board vessel generator in a prohibited area); Isle Royale National 
              Park regulations; Whether the quarter of a mile prohibition was 
              invalid, or arbitrary and capricious; Public notice; Whether regulation 
              was overbroad; Whether defendant was engaged in a First Amendment 
              protest action<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court:</b>  
              U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name:</b>  United States v. Bieti<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number:</b>  12358<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s):</b>  
              McKeague</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Defendant’s 
              misdemeanor conviction for violating 36 C.F.R. § 1.5(a)(1) by operating 
              a permanently installed on-board vessel generator in an area prohibited 
              by Isle Royale National Park regulations was affirmed because the 
              regulatory scheme did not authorize his conduct and the quarter-mile 
              prohibition was not arbitrary and capricious. Defendant admitted 
              at trial that on the date in question his boat was anchored in Duncan 
              Bay, the on-board vessel generator was running, and he was within 
              a quarter-mile of the Duncan Bay campground. Defendant was incorrect 
              that 36 C.F.R. § 2.12(a)(3) allowed him to operate his on-board 
              vessel generator within a quarter-mile of the campground. Defendant’s 
              argument that the quarter-mile setback was arbitrary and capricious 
              was also without merit, and since he admitted he knew about the 
              prohibition, he was not prejudiced by any alleged failure to provide 
              public notice. </font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/091301/12358.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
<hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><a name="9"></a><b><font size=2><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Litigation</font></font></b></td>
        </tr>
        <tr valign="top"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <h4><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">This summary 
              also appears under Employment &amp; Labor Law</font></h4>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues:</b> 
              ERISA; Disability benefits; Motion for judgment on the administrative 
              record<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Lamoreaux v. Medtronic, Inc. <br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12354<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Bell</font></p>
            <p style='text-autospace:none'><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The 
              decision of the defendant’s ERISA board terminating plaintiff's 
              long-term disability benefits was reversed and plaintiff’s benefits 
              were reinstated retroactively. The court found that the great weight 
              of the evidence indicated that plaintiff was disabled under the 
              provisions of the ERISA plan and that the plan administrator was 
              in error. The objective evidence in the record supported the conclusions 
              of plaintiff’s doctor and an independent doctor selected by defendant 
              that plaintiff was disabled. Defendant also asserted that there 
              were at least six jobs in the area that plaintiff was capable of 
              performing, but the weight of the evidence indicated that plaintiff 
              simply could not perform these jobs. The court granted plaintiff's 
              motion for judgment on the administrative record.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/082801/12354.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
            <font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
            to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>Voluntary dismissal of one of two defendants; Costs and attorney 
              fees<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>U.S. District Court Western District of Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Love v. Grand Trunk W. R.R., Inc.<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12365<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Bell</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">Since defendant-Midwest 
              failed to identify any legal prejudice that it or defendant-Grand 
              Trunk would suffer if Midwest was dismissed with prejudice and Grand 
              Trunk did not object, the court granted plaintiffs' motion to dismiss 
              Midwest. Midwest argued that the court should not grant a last minute 
              motion that was brought to gain strategic advantage at trial and 
              that it had a vested interest in the outcome because it was obligated 
              to indemnify Grand Trunk for the full amount of its liability. The 
              court also denied Midwest's request for attorney fees and costs 
              as a condition of dismissal, but agreed to entertain a motion at 
              a later time, if there was sanctionable conduct.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/district/2001/091401/12365.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
            <hr>
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr> 
          <td colspan="1" bgcolor="#ffff80" valign="top"><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><a name="10"></a><b>Tax</b></font></td>
