        <tr valign="top"> 
          <td colspan="3"> 
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="#contents"><font size="-2">Back 
              to Quicklinks</font></a></b></font> </p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>This summary 
              also appears under Employment &amp; Labor Law</b></font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Issues: 
              </b>The State Employees Retirement Act (SERA); Whether the trial 
              court properly determined that monthly payments for accumulated 
              sick leave under a state employee early retirement program were 
              exempt from state, county, city, and other local taxes; Rights and 
              accruals; <i>Ejusdem generis</i>; Absurd result; Necessary joinder; 
              Local taxing authorities; Injunction<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Court: 
              </b>Michigan Court of Appeals (Published)<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Case 
              Name: </b>Stone v. Michigan<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>e-Journal 
              Number: </b>12373<br>
              </font><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b>Judge(s): 
              </b>Whitbeck and Kelly; Dissent - Collins</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3">The Court of 
              Claims properly determined that monthly payments to state employees 
              (hired before October 1, 1980 and retired under the SERA) for accumulated 
              sick leave under a special statutory provision for an early retirement 
              program, are exempt from state, county, city, and other local taxes. 
              Ordinarily, payment for accumulated sick leave to state employees 
              hired before 1980 occurred in a single lump sum, which the state 
              taxed as income the year it was received. The SERA provides that 
              any amount that a member retiring under § 19(f)(3) would otherwise 
              be entitled to receive as a lump sum at retirement on account of 
              accumulated sick leave shall be paid in 60 consecutive equal installments. 
              When the state began making monthly accumulated sick leave payments 
              to plaintiffs under the 1996-97 early retirement program, the state 
              taxed these payments as if they were the traditional lump sum payments, 
              apparently withholding both state and local taxes from the payments. 
              Plaintiffs claimed that defendants could not tax these monthly payments. 
              The court concluded that the Legislature intended to make the tax-exempt 
              provisions of § 40(1) apply to the accumulated sick leave payments 
              under § 19(f)(3). Affirmed</font></p>
            <p><font face="Times New Roman, Times, serif" size="3"><b><a href="http://www.michbar.org/opinions/home.html?/opinions/appeals/2001/092101/12373.html">Full 
              Text Opinion</a></b></font></p>
